# EPR design guide

The house style for the **Epidemic Preparedness and Response** book and every
interactive illustration in it. Read this before adding or changing any figure
so the whole book stays visually consistent.

The single source of truth for values is code, not this file:

- `_brand.yml` -> Quarto theme colours and fonts
- `epr.scss` -> CSS custom properties (`--epr-*`), including illustration tokens
- `js/epr-viz.js` -> the same tokens as a JS fallback (`EPR.colors()`), plus shared math, tweening and injected component CSS

This document explains *what the values mean and how to use them*. If a value
here ever disagrees with the code, the code wins; fix this file.

---

## 1. Principles

1. **Clinical calm.** White canvas, soft slate ink, one cool accent. No gradients, no drop shadows beyond a faint contact shadow, no clutter. Flat, modern, quiet.
2. **The metaphor is the lesson.** An "illustration" here is a playable cartoon or game that builds intuition (the bottle line "overfill tank" for CUSUM), not an abstract chart in nice colours.
3. **One honest scale.** When a picture encodes a quantity, every part of it uses the same pixels-per-unit ruler. Never fudge one element to make it readable.
4. **Mobile first, gesture friendly.** Big type, big tap targets, smooth on a phone. Time always flows left to right.
5. **Design before code.** Agree a storyboard and, where useful, a static mockup before building. Prefer a single screen where everything is visible and live over a Next/Back wizard.
6. **Never use the em dash.** Use a comma, a colon, or "->".

---

## 2. Colour

Colour-blind safe: meaning is carried by blue vs amber/teal (not red/green), plus position and shape. Red and amber are always backed by a second cue (a pulse, a dashed line, the word "OVERFLOW").

### Core tokens

| Token | Hex | Role |
|---|---|---|
| `ink` | `#1f2933` | Foreground text, vial outlines, tank outline |
| `muted` | `#64748b` | Secondary labels, axes, ticks |
| `grid` | `#e7ecf1` | Hairlines, card borders, faint fills |
| `surface` | `#ffffff` | Page and card background |
| `surfaceAlt` | `#f4f7fa` | Inset panels (e.g. the "Now measuring" zoom panel), chips |
| `expected` (teal) | `#0f9b8e` | In-control baseline, the fill line, in-spec liquid, "drift began" marker |
| `accent` (blue) | `#2563eb` | The active statistic, primary buttons, current selection |
| `accentSoft` | `rgba(37,99,235,.13)` | Area under the live statistic, focus ring |
| `alarm` (amber) | `#d97706` | Warning, the overfill above the line (wasted dose) |
| `alarmStrong` (red) | `#dc2626` | Threshold H, alarm state, overflow |

### Illustration tokens (vial + conveyor)

| Token | Hex | Use |
|---|---|---|
| `glass` | `#eef3f8` | Glass body and neck fill |
| `glassStroke` | `#9aa7b5` | Glass outline |
| `cap` | `#8b95a1` | Aluminium flip cap base |
| `capHi` | `#b9c1ca` | Cap highlight block |
| `capEdge` | `#6f7882` | Cap shadow edge |
| `crimp` | `#7e8893` | Crimp ring under the cap |
| `belt` | `#8b98a8` | Conveyor belt |
| `roller` | `#b6c0cc` | Belt rollers |

Read tokens at run time with `EPR.color("expected")` or `EPR.colors()`; never
hard-code a hex in a chapter script except for pure white highlights (`#ffffff`)
and the tiny serration grey.

---

## 3. Typography

- **Family:** Inter (Google), weights 400/500/600/700. Monospace for formulas only: Iosevka, then system mono.
- **Body:** ~18px, line-height 1.65. Headings 600 weight.
- **In SVG figures:** no label below 10.5px in the 760-wide viewBox, and never below 12px for anything the learner must read (chips, axis numbers, the weight bubble). Use `font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums` for any changing number so it does not jiggle.

---

## 4. The vaccine vial (signature component)

Every vial in the book, at any size, is the same object: a small glass vaccine
vial with an aluminium flip cap. Reference photo lives in the team brief; the
drawn version is in `js/cusum.js` (`heroVial`, `beltVial`).

### Anatomy, top to bottom

1. **Aluminium flip cap** (`cap`) with a lighter highlight block (`capHi`) on the upper left and a thin shadow edge (`capEdge`) on the right.
2. **Crimp ring** (`crimp`) with faint vertical serrations.
3. **Neck** (`glass`), narrow.
4. **Shoulder**, a short curve flaring from neck to body.
5. **Glass body** (`glass`, outline `glassStroke`), tall, rounded bottom corners.
6. **Gloss highlights:** one wide soft white streak and one thin bright white streak on the left third of the body. This is what makes flat glass read as glass; do not use gradients.
7. **Liquid:** teal (`expected`) at ~30% opacity, filled to the fill line.
8. **Overfill:** amber (`alarm`) band drawn only for the millilitres above the line.
9. **Label** (hero size only): white rounded rectangle with a barcode (varied-width black bars) on the left and two red bands (`alarmStrong`) to the right.

### Two sizes, one ruler

- **Hero vial:** the vial currently being measured, shown large in a `surfaceAlt`
  inspection panel labelled "Now measuring", with the filler nozzle above, the
  fill line, and the full label. This is where the reference detail lives.
- **Belt vial:** the finished vials lined up on the conveyor, drawn as a compact
  silhouette (cap, neck, body, gloss, liquid, amber top). Too small for a label;
  the silhouette still reads as the same vial.

**Honest scale rule.** The amber overfill height and the tank fill use the *same*
pixels-per-millilitre constant (`PXG`). A 0.2 mL overfill is the same number of
pixels on the hero vial, on a belt vial, and as a rise in the tank. Keep it that
way: it is the whole point of the picture.

### States

| State | Look |
|---|---|
| In spec | teal fill to the line, no amber |
| Over the line | teal fill plus a small amber band above the line |
| More overfill | taller amber band |
| Empty preview | glass only, label faded to ~40% (before the first measurement) |

### Do / don't

- Do keep the cap grey aluminium. Don't use a black or coloured cap.
- Do draw the neck and shoulder. Don't fall back to a plain rounded rectangle (that reads as a test tube).
- Do colour liquid teal and overfill amber. Don't introduce off-palette blues.
- Do show the label and barcode only on the hero. Don't try to cram a barcode onto a 10px belt vial.

---

## 5. Conveyor and tank

- The **belt** runs left to right with rollers underneath; finished vials sit on it in order so the learner sees the whole run.
- The **tank** catches overfill, uses the same `PXG` ruler with ticks at 0 / 0.5 / 1.0 mL, a dashed red `H` stop line, and a small bell that turns amber and shakes on overflow (the shake is skipped under reduced motion).

---

## 6. Shared chart grammar

Every quantitative chart in the book uses the same conventions:

- Time / sequence on the x axis, left to right.
- The expected level is teal; a muted teal band shows the expected range.
- The live statistic is the blue line with a soft blue area fill under it.
- The threshold is a dashed line (amber for a soft limit, red for a hard stop H).
- An alarm is a red dot or a short pulse, never colour alone.

---

## 7. Motion and gestures

- **One pointer model.** Use Pointer Events (`pointerdown` / `pointermove` / `pointerup`) for any drag, with `setPointerCapture` and CSS `touch-action: none` on the draggable element so a phone does not scroll the page while dragging. Do not ship separate mouse and touch code paths.
- **Tap targets** are at least 44px tall (buttons already are in `epr-viz.js`).
- **Animate with** `EPR.tween` (requestAnimationFrame, cubic ease). Keep transitions short (about 240ms) so the line never feels laggy.
- **Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`.** `EPR.tween`, the bell shake and the leak drip already fall back to an instant state; anything new must do the same.
- **Immediate feedback:** show the weight bubble, move the tank, and update the chart on the same click.

---

## 8. Accessibility

- Each figure `<svg>` has `role="img"` and a plain-language `aria-label` (or `<title>` + `<desc>`) describing what it shows.
- Text and meaningful marks meet WCAG AA contrast on white. Buttons have a visible `:focus-visible` ring (`accentSoft`).
- Never rely on colour alone; pair it with shape, position or a word.

---

## 9. Adding a new illustration

1. Storyboard the metaphor and agree it first.
2. In the chapter `.qmd`, add a mount: `<div id="my-fig" class="epr-mount"></div>`, inside `::: {.column-page}` if it should be wide.
3. Write `js/my-fig.js` as an IIFE: read colours with `EPR.colors()`, build SVG with the same helpers used in `cusum.js`, call `EPR.injectStyles()` for the shared component CSS.
4. Load the scripts at the end of the `.qmd`: `epr-viz.js` first, then your file.
5. `js/` is already a Quarto resource in `_quarto.yml`, so files are copied to the build.

### Editor gotcha (important)

A formatter / watcher on the author's machine reformats `.js` files on save and
has **truncated** them mid-write when edited through the normal file tools. Write
JS files in full with a shell heredoc (`cat > js/file.js <<'EOF' ... EOF`), then
run `node --check js/file.js` in the same step. Verify rendering before moving on
(headless jsdom + a rasteriser, or the live Quarto preview).
